4. JSX

JSX stands for:

JavaScript XML

It allows us to write HTML inside JavaScript.

Example
function App() {
  return (
    <h1>Welcome to React</h1>
  );
}

Without JSX:

React.createElement(
  "h1",
  null,
  "Welcome to React"
);

JSX makes code easier to read.

JSX Rules
Single Parent Element

❌ Wrong

return (
  <h1>Hello</h1>
  <p>React</p>
);

✅ Correct

return (
  <div>
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <p>React</p>
  </div>
);

or

return (
  <>
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <p>React</p>
  </>
);
JavaScript inside JSX

Use curly braces {}

function App() {

  const name = "Priyadharshini";

  return (
    <h1>Hello {name}</h1>
  );
}

Output:

Hello Priyadharshini
5. Components

A Component is a reusable piece of UI.

Functional Component
function Welcome() {
  return (
    <h2>Welcome User</h2>
  );
}

export default Welcome;

Use in App.jsx:

import Welcome from './Welcome';

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Welcome />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

Output:

Welcome User
Create Multiple Components
Header.jsx
function Header() {
  return (
    <h1>Library Management System</h1>
  );
}

export default Header;
Footer.jsx
function Footer() {
  return (
    <p>Copyright 2026</p>
  );
}

export default Footer;
App.jsx
import Header from './Header';
import Footer from './Footer';

function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <Header />
      <Footer />
    </>
  );
}

export default App;
